"'''All I Have to Do Is Dream'''" is a [[popular music|popular]] [[song]] made famous by [[the Everly Brothers]], written by the legendary husband and wife songwriting team [[Felice and Boudleaux Bryant]], and published in [[1958 in music|1958]]. The song is ranked #141 on the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].

==The Everly Brothers version==
By far the best-known version was recorded by [[The Everly Brothers]] and released as a single in April 1958. It had been recorded in just two takes <ref>[http://www.acousticguitar.com/issues/ag92/EverlyBrosB.shtml Acoustic Guitar: Everly Brothers Part 2<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> on March 6, 1958 and features [[Chet Atkins]] on guitar. It is the only single to be at #1 on all of Billboard's singles charts simultaneously, on June 2, 1958. It first reached #1 on the "Most played by Jockeys" and "Top 100" charts on [[Hot 100 number-one hits of 1958 (United States)|May 19, 1958]], and remained there for five and three weeks, respectively; with the August 1958 introduction of the [[Billboard Hot 100]] chart, the song ended the year at #2. "All I Have to Do Is Dream" also hit number one on the R&B charts <ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=194}}</ref> as well as becoming The Everly Brothers' third number one on the country chart <ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=117}}</ref>. The Everly Brothers briefly returned to the Hot 100 in 1961 with this song.

The song has also featured on several notable lists of the best songs or singles of all time, including ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 1001 best songs ever in 2003 and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s [[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]], where it placed 141. It was named one of the "500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll" by the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and received the [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]] in 2004.

The [[B-side]], "Claudette", was the first major songwriting success for [[Roy Orbison]], and was named for his wife. As a result of this song he terminated his contract with Sun Records and affiliated himself with the Everly's publisher, Acuff-Rose.

The song appears in the game [[Mafia 2]]. However the game is set in 1951, 7 years before the song was released

==Notable versions==
In 1981, [[Grammy]] winner [[Juice Newton]] included the song on her career-establishing ''Juice'' album.

In 1984, [[Jeff Bridges]]  and [[Karen Allen]] recorded a duet of the song for the film ''[[Starman (film)|Starman]]'' in which they also starred.

A version performed by [[The Dandy Warhols]] was featured in the 2005 videogame ''[[Stubbs the Zombie in Rebel Without a Pulse]]''.

On November 4, 2010, [[Stephen Colbert]] and [[Elvis Costello]] ended "[[The Colbert Report]]" with a duet of the song, the full version of which appeared on the ''ColbertNation'' web site by the following morning.<ref>[http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/364519/november-04-2010/exclusive---elvis-costello---all-i-have-to-do-is-dream Colbert Report website]</ref>

This song was also used in the ending credits in the 2010 film ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]''.

===Hit recordings===
Another well known version was released by [[Richard Chamberlain (actor)|Richard Chamberlain]] on his album ''Richard Chamberlain Sings''. This version became a hit when released as a [[single (music)|single]] in [[1963 in music|1963]], peaking at #14 on the ''Billboard'' pop singles chart.

Other hit versions of the song include duets by [[Bobbie Gentry]] and [[Glen Campbell]] in [[1969 in music|1969]] (#27 U.S. pop, #6 U.S. country, #3 UK) and by [[Andy Gibb]] and actress [[Victoria Principal]] in [[1981 in music|1981]] (#51 U.S.).

[[The Nitty Gritty Dirt Band]]'s version hit #66 on the ''Billboard'' pop chart in 1975. [[Cliff Richard]], singing with Phil Everly of the Everly Brothers, took the song to #14 on the UK singles chart in 1994.

[[R.E.M.]] also covered the song as "(All I've Got to Do Is) Dream".

